l Aramaic inscriptions (10th - 3rd cents. BC) hitherto published; they cover an area extending from Asia Minor, Egypt, Syria and Palestine to Afghanistan. It serves as a reference volume for the concordance, which will be published in 2007 and provides rapid access to the overall context of every reference. Each text is provided with the most important editions and further bibliographical references. The work thus provides scholars with the total corpus of Old and Imperial Aramaic epigraphs in a single volume.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Multiple languages.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aAltaramäisch. 4aAramäisch. 4aInschrift. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh1 aSchwiderski, Dirk, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Theology and Religious Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110638165oZDB-23-GTR0 cprintz978311017454040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311087570640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110875706423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110875706/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-GTRc2000d2014